name: Japanese Garden
review_text:
The closure of this place is inevitable.

With less than 15days to its closure, it is time to grab your camera to take those shots the locations u grew up with. I am very sure you may have at least grew up going here once.

Japanese Garden has been living through many changes in Singapore. It moved from Queenstown to its current location beside Chinese Garden. Not only that, even the surrounding changed as well. The buses are now fitted with aircon whereas it was totally already cooling with d windows opened back then; taxis prices of $1.20 are now long gone; and many more.... But time stood still for this place and it is finally now going to go through a change.. A different pace, a different look and maybe a different vibe.. and we can just hope that you get d same feel after its revamp.

The current beauty and serenity of this place is still the same as how it was back then. If you had been here before for some event or even jz for a stroll, you will see there are lots of traces of the past. I won't dwell on how this place came about or even where the development will head to, but all I would like to do, is encourage the youth to walk the path of what your parents walked on.

Come down for a stroll to enjoy the greenery, the birds that fly by, the bridges and ponds throughout the whole place. What i loved most about the place is the beauty and peace i can never get anywhere in Singapore. Tranquility is something i can never get enough off even after several visits here. So my advice is,
enjoy the place before it gets torn down and revamped.. we wont know what the future holds, so grab the present in image before it is lost............

Oya... it is free to enter the place, so i hope it will entice you further to go! Hehehehe, cheers!

Psst... parking is not available here for now.. so just park opposite the place, at the HDB mscp and walk abit..

#famwithsten

name: Japanese Garden
review_text:
This wasn't the seiwa-en of the late 1970s. The structure and greenery are still there but the magic is somewhat gone. Ditto for the Chinese Garden.

The air of tranquility was snuffed put by the rush of modernisation. Nevertheless, a walk through feels better than that of the clinical Garden by the Bay.

Here there are age old vegetation and sage trees. Not quite that  of the venerable Botanical Gardens (the real deal) but greenery of yesteryear still abounds.

Go, take in whatever is left before they start "reinvigorating" the last vestiges of a green lung that the founders of Jurong put in place

Call me a cynic, but serenity and tranquility is what a garden offers - not activities or opportunities (businesses). Look what happened to Sentosa.

name: Japanese Garden
review_text:
(Translated by Google) A Japanese garden with various misconceptions.
The lotus was blooming on that day and it was beautiful.
It's calmer than the Chinese garden and good for a walk
You can't get there unless you pass through the Chinese Garden
Poor access is a problem

(Original)
色々間違った認識の日本庭園。
当日は蓮が咲いていて綺麗だった
中華庭園よりは落ち着いていて散歩に良いが
中華庭園を抜けていかないと行けない
アクセスの悪さが問題

name: Japanese Garden
review_text:
Территория сада очень ухоженная, зеленая, много птиц, гуляют вараны. Сад окружен водой. Рядом находится Китайский сад. В садах много скульптур. Очень спокойное место, людей не много, гулять одно удовольствие. Рекомендую к посещению.

(Translated by Google)
The territory of the garden is very well-groomed, green, many birds, monitor lizards walk. The garden is surrounded by water. Nearby is the Chinese Garden. There are many sculptures in the gardens. Very quiet place, not many people, walking is a pleasure. I recommend to visit.

name: Japanese Garden

A beautiful and impressive garden. Full of Japanese motif sculptures. Tasteful Japanese buildings. You can go around with a bicycle. The place is big. It also has a very interesting Chinese garden. A lot of walking but worth it
